liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australia's former prime minister, Malcolm Turnbull, has also weighed in on Rupert Murdoch's resignation, saying he's not suprised by the news. "He's built a vast global media empire, and no doubt the business pages will give him credit for that. But he has done enormous damage to the democratic world and, in particular, to the United States. "The anger-tainment ecosystem that Fox News, above all, has created in the US has left America angrier and more divided than it's been at any time since the civil war. It is sought in order to keep its ratings up, it is sought to enrage Americans, divide Americans, and divide them against each other." Turnbull says he doesn't believe much will change under the helm of the media mogul's son, Lachlan Murdoch. "Knowing both of them over a very long period of time, my impression is that Lachlan is more ideologically conservative than Rupert. "I think Rupert has always been fascinated by power - he's drawn to it like a moth is to a flame - and so he's enjoyed exerting the power that he has over the political system. And Rupert's politics have evolved to be broadly right-wing, I would say. "But, I agree, I think Lachlan is, if anything, more ideological than his father. So, I don't think there's going to be any change for the better, that's for sure."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Malcolm Turnbull says Lachlan Murdoch is 'more ideological than his father'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Planet Earth is about to receive a special delivery — the biggest sample yet from an asteroid. A NASA spacecraft will fly by Earth on Sunday and drop off what is expected to be at least a cupful of rubble it grabbed from the asteroid Bennu, closing out a seven-year quest. The sample capsule will parachute into the Utah desert, US, as its mothership, the Osiris-Rex spacecraft, zooms off for an encounter with another asteroid. Scientists anticipate getting about 250 grams of pebbles and dust, much more than the teaspoon or so brought back by Japan from two other asteroids. No other country has fetched pieces of asteroids. These preserved time capsules from the dawn of our solar system could help explain how Earth — and life — came to be. University of Arizona’s Dante Lauretta is the mission’s lead scientist. “I ask myself how many heart-pounding moments can you have in one lifetime because I feel like I might be hitting my limit,” she says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: An asteroid sample is about to land on Earth and it's the biggest one yet

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Good morning and welcome to today's markets live blog. The ASX futures suggest the local market will lose more value in this morning's trading session. US markets all took losses overnight. The Dow Jones lost a touch over 1%, the Nasdaq lost 1.8%, and the S & P500 lost 1.6%. And if we look at the global stock market indices, the board is a sea of red, as they say, except for the volatility index (which is up 15%). So we'll see what happens locally today. Remember, yesterday Australia's market closed down by 1.4%, at 7,065.2 points, which was the lowest level since July 11. Rupert Murdoch has announced he is stepping down as chairman of Fox Corp and News Corp, and handing the reins to his son Lachlan. There'll be a lot of news on that topic today.
